<tr><td><b>Remember When It Matters</b> (Wu et al., 2026)</td><td>Proactive memory agent for long-horizon agents.</td><td>Memory mechanism directly motivated by the failure modes LHTB exposes.</td><td><a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.08716">HF</a> / <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.08716">PDF</a></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>
<p>Three patterns cut across the deep threads:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Benchmarks are now defining the problem more sharply than models are solving it.</b> LHTB and RoboDojo both use dense, capability-oriented evaluation to expose gradients that binary metrics would hide. That is a sign the field is moving from “look, it works” to “where exactly does it fail?”</li>
<li><b>Generative priors and long-horizon control are converging, but not yet connected.</b> GenCeption extracts perception from a video generator; LHTB and RoboDojo measure acting over time. The next interesting question is whether these generative world priors can be turned into the memory, planning, and verification functions that long-horizon agents lack.</li>
<li><b>Reproducibility remains uneven.</b> GenCeption ships no code or weights; RoboDojo and LHTB ship code but require heavy infrastructure to run. Claims about emergent generalization or sim-to-real transfer will not be fully testable until artifacts appear.</li>
</ul>